05929nam a22006975i 9780773566705DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735667057 a10.1515/97807735667052doi  a(DE-B1597)656501  a(OCoLC)732600868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE7708bB75 1997eb 7aPOL0040002bisacsh04a323.1/1970711 aMorrison, Andrea P., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJustice for Natives :bSearching for Common Ground /cAndrea P. Morrison. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tThe Medicine Wheel -- tThe 1990 Conference (Photographs by Andrea Morrison) -- tIntroduction -- tThe 1990 Conference: Conflict, Self-Determination and Native Peoples: Searching for Common Ground -- tOpening Thanksgiving -- tNative Women and The Indian Act: The Struggle For Justice (The Robert S. Litvack Memorial Award) -- tNative Self-Determination and Justice -- tAboriginal Title and Land Claims -- tPanel Three -- tThe 1991 Conference: Lessons from Oka: Forging a Better Relationship -- tOpening Thanksgiving -- tThe Path to Crisis: Origins of Conflict -- tThe Current Picture: Progress or Impasse? -- tWays Forward: The Search for Just Solutions -- tKeynote Speaker -- tThe 1992 Conference Justice For Natives ? -- tBarriers to Justice -- tLegal Issues: Continuing Relations -- tPanel Three: Models for Change -- tEpilogue Opening Remarks -- tDraft United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe collection follows a cycle of remembering the past, learning from the present, and planning for the future. In the first section of the book, "Conflict, Self-Determination, and Native Peoples," contributors, including Mohawk activist Ken Deer, Judge Rejean Paul, and scholar Brian Slattery, look at the historical roots of the conflict between Native and non-Native people, problems in the current justice system, and the movement for Native self-determination. In the second section, "Lessons from Oka," Native leaders Elijah Harper, Matthew Coon-Come, and Diom Romeo Saganash respond to the crisis at Oka and scholars Bruce Clark and Robert Venables consider constitutional alternatives and compare Canadian policy with that in the United States. Looking into the future, the final section, "Justice for Natives?" offers practical alternatives for improving relations, reviews actual measures being taken, and proposes models for change. Some of the solutions raised include increased recognition of Crown fiduciary duties to Native people, co-management strategies for land use, and an independent Native judiciary as envisioned by scholar Leroy Little Bear of Saskatchewan. Justice for Natives makes an important contribution to Native, legal, and policy studies in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aChoksi, Anjali, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotler, Irwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurotte, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarper, Elijah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHudson, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlippenstein, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacasse, Jean-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Oren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id